<h1>Problem 1438 - 1994 IMO, P1 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(m\) and \(n\) be positive integers. Let \(a_1,a_2,\dots,a_m\) be distinct elements of \(\{1,2,\dots,n\}\) such that whenever \(a_i+a_j \le n\) for some \(i,j,1\le i \le j \le m\), there exists \(k, 1\le k \le m\) with \(a_i+a_j= a_k\). Prove that
\[\frac{a_1+a_2+\cdots+a_m}{m} \ge \frac{n+1}{2}.\]</p>
